00:42.180 --> 00:50.440
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. In 1979 two remarkable science fiction
novels that seemed to share a number of amazing coincidences were published. One

00:50.440 --> 00:57.900
of the novels was The Fountains of Paradise, the Hugo Award winner for that year.
Its author was British writer Arthur C. Clarke. The other was Web Between the

00:57.900 --> 01:05.840
Worlds. Its author was Charles Sheffield, also British. Besides the fact that both
authors were British, both novels treated an identical theme: satellites in

01:05.840 --> 01:12.980
geosynchronous Earth orbit or space elevators. Neither author knew that someone
else is working with the same idea but Sheffield doesn't believe it's that

01:12.980 --> 01:22.760
startling a coincidence. It's not really very surprising because the idea has
been around a long time. The idea was proposed back in 1960 and I read of it in

01:22.760 --> 01:34.440
1960, in 1966, I read of it, which was the first time it was published in the west. 
A russian called Art Sutanov published it in 1960 but he published it in Russian

01:34.440 --> 01:43.980
in a publication that no one ever saw or heard of, but I remember the 1966
publication in Science Magazine and thinking that's a neat idea and putting it

01:43.980 --> 01:55.640
off in the back of my head and uh presumably several others had noticed it and
thought of it at the same time. And it's coincidence that Clarke and I should

01:55.640 --> 02:06.760
write the books so close together, but in a sense, uh if the books hadn't been
written so close together they would not both have been written because when

02:06.760 --> 02:16.800
somebody has written a book on a subject like that, there's a tendency for other
people not to write uh with that same technological development. Sheffield says

02:16.800 --> 02:24.480
there was something coincidental about his discovery before publication of
either book that Clarke had done the same thing that he had. The coincidence was

02:24.480 --> 02:33.840
that after as I had reached the point where I'd sent my manuscript off to Ace
Books and a friend of mine said that he heard that Clarke had written this book

02:33.840 --> 02:44.760
which was then available in galleys in which he had a space elevator. And when I
read the book, I sent Clarke my manuscript and he wrote back and said he was

02:44.760 --> 02:56.060
fascinated, but he wasn't that surprised and when I read his book I realized what
he meant by that. What he meant was that when you get right down to it, the basic

02:56.060 --> 03:08.680
physics dictates what the uh structure must be like and it's very natural to
have your hero previously making a bridge of a bridge builder because this is in

03:08.680 --> 03:19.480
a sense a bridge from the earth up to orbit. Uh we had both in fact chosen heroes
with very similar names that was a coincidence. His hero was called Morgan. Mine

03:19.480 --> 03:29.320
was called Merlin, and before they built the space elevator they had both been
the world's leading builder of bridges. Sheffield goes on to relate some of the

03:29.320 --> 03:39.880
less obvious similarities about the two novels but there were some other rather
strange coincidences that were not obvious from the from reading the books. One

03:39.880 --> 03:54.720
of them was when I was thinking of my of my principal character, I had as a model
for him a 19th century English engineer called Brunel. Well it turned out that

03:54.720 --> 04:04.760
Clarke actually had Brunel in his book and references to him, and that's an odd
coincidence that is perhaps explained by the fact that the Clarke came from

04:04.760 --> 04:13.420
England and so did I and we were sensitive to the English engineering tradition.
That's the only way I can explain that but there were a number of coincidences.

04:13.420 --> 04:24.300
It's not too surprising that we should write books in which the beanstalk or
space elevator looks very similar but there are other things that that are a bit

04:24.300 --> 04:33.680
more surprising than that, but as one of my as one of my characters keeps on
saying in a different book, uh the laws of probability don't just permit

04:33.680 --> 04:42.900
coincidences they absolutely require them, and to me it's not that surprising
that Clarke and I should have written the same book at the same time. Not the same

04:42.900 --> 04:50.720
book if you follow me but books with with a similar theme. Science fiction
readers should feel fortunate coincidences or not that both of these remarkable

04:50.720 --> 04:51.700
novels were published.

