06:31.580 --> 06:39.740
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Charles Sheffield belongs to that small
subgroup of science fiction authors who are practicing scientists. Hal Clement,

06:39.740 --> 06:47.020
Robert Forward, Fred Hoyle, and soon Carl Sagan will be some other authors in the
group. Sheffield, who has a degree in theoretical physics and works for the Earth

06:47.020 --> 06:54.860
Satellite Corporation in Washington DC, has published such popular novels as Web
Between the Worlds, Site of Proteus, and My Brother's Keeper in addition to

06:54.860 --> 07:05.160
numerous short stories. We asked him how he found time to be a scientist and a
science fiction author. Well I don't write as much as uh as what my wife would

07:05.160 --> 07:16.900
call real writers write. Uh full-time writers should be able to produce a lot
more than I do. One reason I produce as much as I do produce is because I enjoy

07:16.900 --> 07:27.360
it. I consider it a form of pleasure and relaxation and so I do it for choice
when I'm not doing other things but I feel that that if I didn't have a job I

07:27.360 --> 07:37.600
might write a lot more but I would probably enjoy it a lot less and in terms of
somebody who is prolific I don't produce much at all if you look at the

07:37.600 --> 07:49.660
productivity of, well now I have to think of somebody who's prolific, I suppose.
Andy Offutt has written a couple of hundred books probably. Uh C. J. Cherryh produces

07:49.660 --> 08:01.360
I think probably three books a year. Jack Chalker produces probably five books a
year. Silverberg when he was writing full time produced lord knows how many words

08:01.360 --> 08:12.040
a year one and a half million two million something like this. Hh in terms of
productive people, I have a minute output when we remarked that many readers

08:12.040 --> 08:19.180
liked his fiction so well they'd wish he'd take up writing full time and produce
more of it. He had an interesting response: I appreciate the compliment but I

08:19.180 --> 08:32.060
suspect that that if I had more time I wouldn't write that much more. I would
find other ways of of doing things I probably if I had half a day to write. Uh in

08:32.060 --> 08:43.020
other words if I worked half time at my job instead of full time, I would produce
more but I might saturate because it would cease to be enjoyable after doing it

08:43.020 --> 08:54.260
for a certain period each day. The definition that people use of a real writer is
somebody who has to write, who will starve if they can't write, and will write

08:54.260 --> 09:03.140
even if they have to starve. I don't know if that makes sense by those terms I
don't consider i'm a real writer at all because although I like to write it's

09:03.140 --> 09:14.840
not the top of my priority of things I want to do and the scientific work
occupies a higher slot. Uh Marion Zimmer Bradley said that when when she had to

09:14.840 --> 09:25.360
choose between uh a marriage and her writing or anything else, in her writing her
writing wins that. It's the most important thing in her life. I just don't have

09:25.360 --> 09:37.340
that much uh attachment to it and I think the fact that I didn't write for so
long that I started uh for no particular reason after not writing for a long

09:37.340 --> 09:47.840
time may maybe uh one of the reasons I don't consider I'm a a true writer. I
never felt the urge to write when I was young. I never felt that fiction was

09:47.840 --> 10:01.460
something I had to do but many writers have that and it dominates their lives.
Finally we asked Sheffield if he had fun writing. I think I do I certainly love

10:01.460 --> 10:12.280
to sit down and write. I often don't have time to do it but that's a different
consideration. I find that that the several things that help me one is that I

10:12.280 --> 10:25.360
don't have to do it that uh that I'm doing it as a hobby. Another is that I write
lots of non-fiction and when I write non-fiction I'm constrained in what I can

10:25.360 --> 10:34.980
think. In other words if you're writing respectable science you somewhat have to
put yourself into a into an acceptable framework and if you think outrageous

10:34.980 --> 10:44.120
thoughts you can't really write them down or you have to limit yourself whereas
in fiction you can think the most outrageous thoughts imaginable and generally

10:44.120 --> 10:55.840
speaking the more outrageous they are the more people like them. So I do enjoy
writing. This

