12:23.740 --> 12:31.700
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. Marion Zimmer Bradley's latest novel is a
fantasy epic that deals with the legends of King Arthur. It's entitled The Mists

12:31.700 --> 12:38.940
of Avalon, and it's recently been published in a hardcover edition by Alfred A.
Knopf. There are numerous retellings of the Arthurian material, some scholarly,

12:39.200 --> 12:46.680
some pure fantasy, but The Mists of Avalon is different. In the first place,
it's built around a strong thesis, that the rise of Arthur as a Christian king

12:46.680 --> 12:54.780
in a male-dominated society, coincided with the passing away of the old pagan
religion of the Celtic Druids, which was female-oriented. And secondly, Bradley

12:54.780 --> 13:03.220
concentrates her narrative on the women of the Arthurian legends. These would
include Guinevere, Arthur's wife and queen, Igraine, his mother, Viviane, the

13:03.220 --> 13:11.160
lady of the lake and high priestess of Avalon, and Morgaine, or Morgan Le Fay,
sorceress and wizard lady. Bradley tells us how she came to write the book.

13:12.140 --> 13:21.040
Well, all my life I've been fascinated by King Arthur, but even more, I've been
fascinated by Morgan Le Fay. Mallory didn't approve of her, and she's been

13:21.040 --> 13:31.480
treated as a sort of evil sorceress, you know, quote-unquote. And you can hear
the capital letters all the way from Texas, I'm sure. So I started wondering who

13:31.480 --> 13:39.560
Morgan Le Fay and the lady of the lake really were. And there were a lot of
books on the search for the historical Arthur, but I started out on the search

13:39.560 --> 13:50.980
for the historical Morgan Le Fay. How did she get into the legends? And it led
me into the byways of pagan religions, into Druidism, into, I don't mean the

13:50.980 --> 14:06.200
modern thing, but what Caesar wrote about, and enormous amounts of ancient, you
might say ancient culture. So I finally came up with the realization that the

14:06.200 --> 14:19.520
whole Arthurian cycle is based upon the shift from Druidical and Celtic
religions to Christianity. And in the Celtic culture and the Celtic mythology

14:19.520 --> 14:29.180
and the Celtic religion, women were preeminent, whereas in Christianity, St.
Jerome and St. Augustine tried to convince every woman that she should be

14:29.180 --> 14:38.240
constantly doing penance and covered with shame for the very fact that she was a
woman. And that ghastly culture shock, I think, pervaded the whole Arthurian

14:38.240 --> 14:47.360
mythos. Mallory didn't get hold of it until later. The novel is remarkable for
its wealth of detail and its attention to character, both strong points in all

14:47.360 --> 14:54.520
of Marion Zimmer Bradley's work. All of the characters from the Arthurian
legends come alive in the novel, people like Merlin, Gawaine, and Galahad.

14:54.980 --> 15:02.660
Lancelot is in the novel, of course, and his love of Guinevere is sensitively
handled by Bradley. Bradley talks about the ideas beneath the novel. I took one

15:02.660 --> 15:15.820
element of fantasy, the idea that as our beliefs in the world change, our world
changes with it. The idea that people used to act and believe as if the world

15:15.820 --> 15:22.760
were the center of the universe, and now we know that the sun is at the center
of our galaxy, but that we're way out on the edge of it, and that changes our

15:22.760 --> 15:34.360
relationship to ourselves and our world. When people believed that the source of
life was just the mother, that was one belief system which very firmly and

15:34.360 --> 15:45.820
deeply pervaded their consciousnesses. And then when the idea came that the
mother was incidental, that man was created in God's image and women was just a

15:45.820 --> 15:58.600
poor imitation, it must have been a monster culture shock. And so I gave the
idea that the world actually changed at that time, that the religion, the idea

15:58.600 --> 16:09.460
of only having one God instead of a pantheon of God, changed people's minds. So
I took one fantasy element, the idea that as these old worlds, as people's ideas

16:09.460 --> 16:19.960
changed, the world changed too. So the world where the elves lived sort of went
into another dimension, being replaced by a world of pagan religion. And then

16:19.960 --> 16:28.960
when the world changed again, the world of pagan religion, what I call the world
of Avalon, went into the mists. Anyone who likes fantasy, or anyone who enjoys

16:28.960 --> 16:36.080
reading about King Arthur, will be fascinated with the Mists of Avalon. And the
fascination should last for a long while too. In its hardcover format, the novel

16:36.080 --> 16:38.780
is over 800 pages. The word epic describes it well.

